# Summary

The paper presents a method to create universal, robust, targeted adversarial image patches that can fool classifiers in the real world. The key ideas are:

- The patches are universal - they work on any image by completely replacing part of the image. The patch is trained on a variety of images with random translations, scaling, and rotations. This makes it scene-independent.

- The patches are robust because they work under transformations like lighting, orientation, scale changes. This is achieved by training with random transformations.

- The patches are targeted to output any target class. The patch optimizes the probability of the target class over transformations, images, and locations.

- The patches can be printed out and added to any real world scene to cause a classifier to ignore other items and report the target class. This is demonstrated on ImageNet classifiers like VGG16, InceptionV3 etc.

- The attack does not require knowing the image or scene. The patch can be widely distributed. Defenses against small perturbations may not work against this larger perturbation.

- The patch can also be camouflaged by optimizing it to look like a specific starting image.

# Summary bullet points

* Presents method to create universal, robust, targeted adversarial patches 
* Patches work by replacing part of any image, train over images and transformations
* Optimization maximizes target class probability over images, locations and transformations
* Patches fool classifiers when printed out and added to real world scenes
* Works without knowing lighting, angle, other items in scene
* Can distribute patch widely since does not depend on image
* Defenses against small perturbations may fail against larger patches
* Can camouflage patch by optimizing to look like a starting image

